---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="About Sajiv Francis — Enterprise Architect leading AI programmes at a Fortune 50 technology company. Indo-Canadian living in Arizona."
  mainClass="max-w-5xl"
>
  <!-- Hero: text left, curved portrait right.
       The photo's left edge is shaped with an elliptical border-radius so
       it reads editorial rather than a fitted rectangle. Stacks on mobile. -->
  <section class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-[1.1fr_1fr] gap-10 md:gap-14 items-center mb-16">
    <div>
      <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-wider text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-400 mb-3">
        About
      </p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-semibold tracking-tight mb-4">
        Sajiv Francis
      </h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300 mb-6 leading-snug">
        Enterprise Architect — AI programmes, cloud, and SAP ecosystems.
      </p>
      <p class="text-base text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed">
        Indo-Canadian living in Arizona. I lead AI programmes at a Fortune 50
        technology company and build
        <a href="/" class="underline underline-offset-4 decoration-neutral-400 hover:decoration-current">Gravitite</a>
        on the side.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="hero-photo-frame">
      <img
        src="/img/authors/sajivfrancis.jpg"
        alt="Portrait of Sajiv Francis"
        class="hero-photo"
        width="399"
        height="450"
        loading="eager"
      />
    </div>
  </section>

  <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
    <h2>Now <span class="not-prose text-sm font-normal text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-400 align-middle">— May 2026</span></h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Leading AI programmes at a Fortune 50 technology company.</li>
      <li>Building Gravitite, an AI-native enterprise architecture platform.</li>
      <li>Writing about agentic architectures, MCP and A2A protocols, and the SAP S/4HANA ecosystem.</li>
      <li>TOGAF 10 certified. Stanford AI-Driven Leadership.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Background</h2>
    <p>
      Eight years of building at the intersection of AI and enterprise
      systems — from a 2018 grad-school location tool for Connecticut seniors,
      to an NLP-powered adaptive learning system in 2019 (predating mainstream
      RAG by four years), to enterprise data orchestration on Kubernetes, to
      leading AI programmes inside one of the world's largest technology
      companies.
    </p>

    <h2>Why this work</h2>
    <p>
      I came into enterprise architecture sideways — through software
      engineering, then through trying to make AI useful inside organisations
      that move slowly. What I care about now is the seam where new model
      capabilities meet decades-old enterprise systems, and how architects
      translate one to the other without breaking either.
    </p>

    <h2>Life outside work</h2>
    <p>
      Married, two kids. Most weekends are theirs.
    </p>
    <p>
      When time allows: I ride a Harley, collect stamps (a habit my
      grandfather used to do, decades ago, that I've never quite outgrown)
      and I also pretend to follow Formula 1 and MotoGP as closely as I once did.
    </p>

    <h2>Education &amp; communities</h2>
    <div class="not-prose grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-x-10 gap-y-2 my-6 text-base">
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-400 mb-2">Education</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-1 list-none p-0">
          <li>M.S. Software Engineering — <a href="https://www.fairfield.edu" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="underline underline-offset-4 decoration-neutral-400">Fairfield University</a></li>
          <li>Applied Data Science — <a href="https://www.engineering.columbia.edu" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="underline underline-offset-4 decoration-neutral-400">Columbia Engineering</a></li>
          <li>AI-Driven Leadership — <a href="https://online.stanford.edu" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="underline underline-offset-4 decoration-neutral-400">Stanford</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-400 mb-2">Communities</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-1 list-none p-0">
          <li>Association of Enterprise Architects (AEA)</li>
          <li>ASUG (Americas' SAP Users' Group)</li>
          <li>The Open Group — TOGAF certified member</li>
          <li>Arizona Science &amp; Engineering Fair (judge)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Writing</h2>
    <p>
      I write about the future of architecture practice at the intersection of
      AI and organisational design — for practitioners, not just academics.
      Recent pieces are on the <a href="/blog/">writing</a> page.
    </p>

    <h2>Contact</h2>
    <p>
      <a href="mailto:connectsfrancis@gmail.com">connectsfrancis@gmail.com</a>
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  /* Curved-edge portrait. The left edge is shaped by an asymmetric
     elliptical border-radius — gentler at the bottom-left than the
     top-left so it reads organic rather than half-pill. Right edge
     stays square so the photo can visually bleed into the page edge
     on wide screens without fighting the curve. */
  .hero-photo-frame {
    position: relative;
    width: 100%;
    aspect-ratio: 4 / 5;
    overflow: hidden;
    border-radius: 55% 12px 12px 55% / 60% 12px 12px 50%;
    box-shadow: 0 20px 60px -20px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.25);
  }

  .hero-photo {
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center top;
    display: block;
  }

  /* On wide screens, let the photo nudge slightly past the page
     gutter so it feels like it "spans" the right side rather than
     sitting politely inside the column. */
  @media (min-width: 1024px) {
    .hero-photo-frame {
      margin-right: -2rem;
    }
  }

  /* Soften the shadow in dark mode (deep shadows on a dark bg look muddy). */
  :global(html[data-theme='dark']) .hero-photo-frame {
    box-shadow: 0 20px 60px -20px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.6);
  }
</style>
